          <avActivityHighlights>Wind slabs require caution.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The storm force wind has transported the fresh and old snow significantly. &lt;br/&gt; The hard wind slabs of the last three days are lying on a crust in particular on sunny slopes and at high altitude. These can be released by a single winter sport participant. In particular on steep north, northeast and northwest facing slopes the avalanches can be triggered in the faceted old snow and reach quite a large size. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Caution is to be exercised on wind-loaded slopes, and in gullies and bowls.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>In some regions 10 to 15 cm of snow, and up to 20 cm in some localities, fell on Wednesday. &lt;br/&gt; The foehn wind has transported the fresh and old snow significantly. Over a wide area wind slabs are lying on a hard crust. &lt;br/&gt; In particular adjacent to ridgelines at high altitude snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of low temperatures the snowpack can not consolidate, in particular on shady slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The solar radiation will give rise to gradual consolidation of the snowpack in particular on sunny slopes.</tendencyComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
    </Bulletin>
