          <avActivityHighlights>The wind slabs are to be assessed with care and prudence.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The northwesterly wind has transported the fresh and old snow significantly. The hard wind slabs are lying on a crust in particular on sunny slopes and at high altitude. &lt;br/&gt; These can in isolated cases be released, even by a single winter sport participant and reach medium size. The avalanche prone locations are to be found in particular in gullies and bowls and on wind-loaded slopes. Along the border with France the likelihood of avalanches is higher. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Backcountry touring calls for caution. &lt;br/&gt;</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>The foehn wind has transported the fresh and old snow significantly. Over a wide area wind slabs are lying on a hard crust, especially on sunny slopes in all altitude zones, and adjacent to ridgelines and in pass areas at elevated altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; High altitudes shady slopes: Towards its base, the snowpack is faceted. &lt;br/&gt; Individual weak layers exist in the centre of the snowpack especially on west, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; On sunnier slopes where temperatures are less cold, the hard surface of the snowpack will gradually soften over the course of the day. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular adjacent to ridgelines at high altitude snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind.</snowpackStructureComment>
